description.original: Use number-prefixes in your file names to define a custom order, and drag-and-drop the files to update that order
description.translation: Use number-prefixes in your file names to define a custom order, and drag-and-drop the files to update that order

dict.Notice(\"Prefix min length must be a num: Notice("Prefix min length must be a number above or equal zero.")
dict.Notice(\"Starting index must be a number: Notice("Starting index must be a number above or equal zero.")
dict..error(\"forceFrameRate takes a positive: .error("forceFrameRate takes a positive int between 0 and 125, forcing frame rates higher than 125 fps is not supported")
dict.text:'To reorder files, right click on a: text:'To reorder files, right click on any file in the file explorer, and click on "Reorder items".'
dict..setDesc(\"Prefix numbers will be padded: .setDesc("Prefix numbers will be padded to that length if they are shorted, i.e. 001 instead of 1")
dict..setDesc(\"Delimiter between prefix numb: .setDesc("Delimiter between prefix number and title. May be multiple characters.")
dict..setDesc(\"RegEx of files and folder to: .setDesc("RegEx of files and folder to ignore. Eg: ^index\\.md$ to ignore index.md files")
dict..setDesc(\"In a folder named MyFolderNam: .setDesc("In a folder named MyFolderName, ignore MyFolderName.md")
dict.text:'The following settings are default: text:'The following settings are defaults for when items are reordered for the first time in a folder. Subsequent reorders will always reuse the existing settings for the respective folder, and the settings can be changed per folder by clicking the down-icon-button in the reorder view next to the "Files" or "Folders" headers.'
